4. Explore the possibility of analyzing entry events in a similar manner as exit events, allowing for a comprehensive understanding of trade dynamics.

5. Further enhance the exit cost control point (CCP) and partial cost control point (CCP) logic to improve decision-making and optimize trade outcomes.

6. Enhance the cost control point (CCP) logic to handle cases where trimming following a rebalance is correctly labeled as cost control (CP), ensuring accurate trade labeling.

7. Conduct an analysis of additional events such as the time between exit and re-entry, as well as tracking short and long positions after an exit, providing valuable insights into trade patterns and potential opportunities.

8. Study the purchases made by the portfolio manager when selling a holding and compare their performance, aiming to gain insights into the effectiveness of the manager's decision-making.

9. Implement the framework on a long-only fund tied to a benchmark, aiming to make the investment strategy more robust and aligned with benchmark performance.

